{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17649685","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17649685"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T21:07:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T21:07:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18375"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"18375","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/18375"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11093"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80755"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11093","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11093"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18375"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66055"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4931"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7461"},{"type":"tags","id":"7462"},{"type":"tags","id":"11399"},{"type":"tags","id":"11400"},{"type":"tags","id":"11401"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"25724"},{"type":"contributions","id":"25729"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80755","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/80755"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following joints is primarily involved in ankle trauma?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Subtalar joint","Talo-crural joint","Tibiofibular joint","Metatarsophalangeal joints","Calcaneocuboid joint"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etalo-crural joint\u003C/strong\u003E is also known as the ankle joint, and is the joint primarily involved in ankle trauma. The joint is formed by the articulation of the talus, tibia and fibula and is responsible for dorsiflexion and plantar flexion of the foot.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Esubtalar joint\u003C/strong\u003E is located below the talo-crural joint, and allows for eversion and inversion of the foot. While it can be involved in ankle injuries, it is not the primary joint affected in most ankle traumas.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etibiofibular joint\u003C/strong\u003E is the articulation between the tibia and fibula. It is not typically the main joint involved in ankle injuries, although it can be affected in high ankle sprains.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Emetatarsophalangeal joints\u003C/strong\u003E are located in the forefoot and are not involved in ankle trauma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ecalcaneocuboid joint\u003C/strong\u003E is part of the midfoot and is not primarily involved in ankle injuries.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The talo-crural joint is the primary joint involved in ankle trauma.","Assessment of ankle injuries should include evaluation of other tarsal bones, joints, and structures such as tendons and nerves."],"references":["Patton, K. T., \u0026 Thibodeau, G. A. (2018). Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book: Anthony\u0027s Textbook of Anatomy \u0026 Physiology-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Smith, R., \u0026 Wordsworth, P. (2016). Oxford textbook of clinical and biochemical disorders of the skeleton. Oxford University Press","Sud, A., \u0026 Ranjan, R. (2021). Textbook of Orthopaedics, 2e-E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","Dandy, D. J., \u0026 Edwards, D. J. (2009). Essential Orthopaedics and Trauma E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences","MacGregor R, Byerly DW. Anatomy, Bony Pelvis and Lower Limb: Foot Bones. 2023 May 23. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan\u2013. PMID: 32491379"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66055"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"18375"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"66055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/66055"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-22T16:35:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-22T16:36:06+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11093"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"80755"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4931","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4931"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddb4","name":"Musculoskeletal","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T09:50:31+10:30"},"